[{"location":"functions/#API-Reference","page":"API Reference","title":"API Reference","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"functions/#Core-Types-And-Solver","page":"API Reference","title":"Core Types And Solver","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"functions/","page":"API Reference","title":"API Reference","text":"PolaronMobility\nAbstractPolaronModel\nAbstractContinuumModel\nAbstractLatticeModel\nAbstractMaterial\nAbstractTrialProcess\nAbstractJumpTrial\nAbstractGaussianTrial\nVariationalProblem\nVariationalResult\nObservableResult\nOptimizerOptions\nEnergyComponents\nPolaronResult\nsolve\nsolve_variational\nobjective\nfree_energy\nentropy_cost\ninteraction_free_energy\nparameter_names","category":"page"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility","text":"PolaronMobility\n\nVariational polaron models, mobility estimates, and frequency-dependent transport response.\n\nCore calculations are dimensionless and organized around a generic VariationalProblem(model, trial) pipeline. The package currently provides continuum Fröhlich Gaussian trials, lattice Holstein and Peierls Poisson trials, and compatible lattice model composition.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"module"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.AbstractPolaronModel","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.AbstractPolaronModel","text":"AbstractPolaronModel\n\nSupertype for dimensionless physical polaron models. Concrete models provide couplings, dispersions, lattice parameters, or material metadata.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.AbstractContinuumModel","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.AbstractContinuumModel","text":"AbstractContinuumModel\n\nSupertype for continuum/path-integral polaron models with Gaussian trial processes.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.AbstractLatticeModel","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.AbstractLatticeModel","text":"AbstractLatticeModel\n\nSupertype for lattice/worldline polaron models with jump-process trial spaces.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.AbstractMaterial","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.AbstractMaterial","text":"AbstractMaterial\n\nSupertype for material metadata objects that live at API/unit-conversion boundaries. Concrete materials derive dimensionless model parameters but are not used inside low-level physics kernels.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.AbstractTrialProcess","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.AbstractTrialProcess","text":"AbstractTrialProcess\n\nSupertype for variational trial processes. A concrete trial defines its parameter names, initial parameters, bounds, and free/entropy objective terms.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.AbstractJumpTrial","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.AbstractJumpTrial","text":"AbstractJumpTrial\n\nSupertype for jump-process trial families used by lattice polaron models.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.AbstractGaussianTrial","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.AbstractGaussianTrial","text":"AbstractGaussianTrial\n\nSupertype for Gaussian trial processes used with continuum Fröhlich models. Concrete trials define a mean-square-displacement kernel plus trial entropy terms.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.VariationalProblem","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.VariationalProblem","text":"VariationalProblem(model, trial)\n\nPair a concrete polaron model with a compatible trial process. Generic solvers minimize free_energy + entropy_cost + interaction_free_energy.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.VariationalResult","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.VariationalResult","text":"VariationalResult\n\nOptimized variational parameters and objective decomposition at one inverse temperature beta.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.ObservableResult","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.ObservableResult","text":"ObservableResult\n\nGeneric observable container for extension APIs that only need temperature, inverse temperature, and diagnostics.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.OptimizerOptions","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.OptimizerOptions","text":"OptimizerOptions(; lower=nothing, upper=nothing, initial_parameters=nothing, ...)\n\nNumerical controls shared by all variational solvers. Bounds and initial parameters use the parameter order reported by parameter_names(trial). Trial-specific defaults live on the trial type, not in these global options.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.EnergyComponents","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.EnergyComponents","text":"EnergyComponents\n\nFröhlich energy/free-energy breakdown: total, trial oscillator contribution, interaction contribution, and trial correction.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.PolaronResult","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.PolaronResult","text":"PolaronResult\n\nFull solve result over temperature and frequency grids for a concrete model-trial pair. zero_temperature stores the beta = Inf solution used as the warm-start anchor even for lattice solves.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.solve","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.solve","text":"solve(problem::VariationalProblem{FrohlichModel,<:AbstractGaussianTrial}; temperatures=[0], frequencies=[0], options=OptimizerOptions())\n\nSolve a Fröhlich Gaussian variational problem on reduced temperature and frequency grids, returning a PolaronResult.\n\n\n\n\n\nsolve(problem::VariationalProblem{HolsteinModel,PoissonTrial}; temperatures, frequencies, options)\n\nSolve a Holstein-Poisson variational problem over temperature and frequency grids. Direct model inputs are dimensionless. If the model was built by material_to_problem(::HolsteinMaterial), temperatures are interpreted as Kelvin and frequencies as THz.\n\n\n\n\n\nsolve(problem::VariationalProblem{PeierlsModel,PoissonTrial}; temperatures, frequencies, options)\n\nSolve a Peierls-Poisson variational problem over temperature and frequency grids. Direct inputs are dimensionless. Material-derived problems interpret temperatures as Kelvin and frequencies as THz.\n\n\n\n\n\nsolve(problem::VariationalProblem{CompositePolaronModel,PoissonTrial}; temperatures, frequencies, options)\n\nSolve a compatible composite lattice model over temperature and frequency grids using a shared Poisson trial.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.solve_variational","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.solve_variational","text":"solve_variational(problem, beta; options=OptimizerOptions(), initial_parameters_override=nothing, use_multistart=options.multistart)\n\nOptimize one VariationalProblem at inverse temperature beta, returning a VariationalResult with named parameters, objective components, and optimizer diagnostics.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.objective","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.objective","text":"objective(problem, parameters, beta; options=OptimizerOptions())\n\nEvaluate the full variational objective for a VariationalProblem as free_energy + entropy_cost + interaction_free_energy.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.free_energy","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.free_energy","text":"free_energy(trial, parameters, beta)\n\nReference/free contribution of a trial process to the variational objective.\n\n\n\n\n\nfree_energy(trial::PoissonTrial, parameters, beta)\n\nBare continuous-time random-walk energy for the symmetric nearest-neighbor Poisson trial process.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.entropy_cost","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.entropy_cost","text":"entropy_cost(trial, parameters, beta)\n\nRelative-entropy or trial-correction contribution to the variational objective.\n\n\n\n\n\nentropy_cost(trial::PoissonTrial, parameters, beta)\n\nDonsker-Varadhan relative-entropy rate for changing the bare hopping rate to the variational hopping rate.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.interaction_free_energy","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.interaction_free_energy","text":"interaction_free_energy(model, trial, parameters, beta; kwargs...)\n\nModel/trial interaction contribution to the variational objective.\n\n\n\n\n\ninteraction_free_energy(model::HolsteinModel, trial::PoissonTrial, parameters, beta; rtol=1e-4)\n\nFull-periodic retarded local Holstein interaction evaluated against the CTMC site-return bridge. At zero temperature this reduces to -g² holstein_integral_d(κ, d, ω).\n\n\n\n\n\ninteraction_free_energy(model::PeierlsModel, trial::PoissonTrial, parameters, beta; rtol=1e-4)\n\nFull-periodic retarded Peierls bond influence evaluated against the CTMC bond-order bridge. At zero temperature this reduces to -0.5 g² peierls_integral_d(κ, d, ω).\n\n\n\n\n\ninteraction_free_energy(composite, trial, parameters, beta; rtol=1e-4)\n\nComposite lattice interaction free energy, implemented as the sum of component influence functionals evaluated on the same Poisson path measure.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.parameter_names","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.parameter_names","text":"parameter_names(trial)\n\nReturn the symbolic names of a trial process's variational parameters in solver order.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"functions/#Fröhlich","page":"API Reference","title":"Fröhlich","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"functions/","page":"API Reference","title":"API Reference","text":"FrohlichModel\nGaussianFeynmanTrial\nMultiGaussianTrial\nProfileGaussianTrial\nNonlocalGaussianTrial\nfrohlich_feynman_problem\nfrohlich_multi_gaussian_problem\nfrohlich_profile_gaussian_problem\nfrohlich_nonlocal_gaussian_problem\nsolve_frohlich\nFrohlichSolution\nFrohlichMobilityResult\nFrohlichResponseResult\nfeynman_v\nfeynman_w\nmulti_gaussian_v\nmulti_gaussian_w\nmean_square_displacement\nprofile_function","category":"page"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.FrohlichModel","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.FrohlichModel","text":"FrohlichModel(alpha, phonon_frequencies=1; dimension=3, band_mass=1, ...)\n\nDimensionless continuum Fröhlich model. alpha and phonon_frequencies may be scalars or equal-length vectors for multimode materials.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.GaussianFeynmanTrial","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.GaussianFeynmanTrial","text":"GaussianFeynmanTrial(; dimension=3, initial_v=3.11, initial_w=2.87, ...)\n\nFeynman's two-parameter Gaussian trial process for the continuum Fröhlich polaron. The optimized coordinates are (w, delta) with v = w + delta.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.MultiGaussianTrial","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.MultiGaussianTrial","text":"MultiGaussianTrial(; modes, dimension=3, initial_v=nothing, initial_w=nothing, ...)\n\nFinite-mode Gaussian trial process for Fröhlich variational calculations. The solver parameter order is w1, delta1, w2, delta2, ..., with v_i = w_i + delta_i. For modes = 1 this reduces to Feynman's two-parameter Gaussian trial.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.ProfileGaussianTrial","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.ProfileGaussianTrial","text":"ProfileGaussianTrial(; basis_frequencies, dimension=3, ...)\n\nGeneral Gaussian profile-function trial for Fröhlich polarons. The quadratic trial action is represented by a positive memory profile Γ(ω) = sum(aᵢ νᵢ² / (ω² + νᵢ²)), with optimized amplitudes a1, a2, ... and fixed positive basis frequencies νᵢ.\n\nThe zero-temperature functional uses the standard Gaussian log-determinant entropy term. The mean-square displacement is evaluated by analytically decomposing the rational profile into oscillator kernels, so the one-pole choice Γ(ω) = (v² - w²)/(ω² + w²) reproduces Feynman's one-mode trial exactly.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.NonlocalGaussianTrial","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.NonlocalGaussianTrial","text":"NonlocalGaussianTrial(; basis_frequencies, dimension=3, ...)\n\nExperimental Gaussian trial specified directly by a finite nonlocal memory kernel basis. Parameters are positive basis amplitudes a1, a2, ..., and the mean-square displacement is built from a sum of oscillator kernels at fixed basis_frequencies.\n\nThis type is intended as an extensible kernel scaffold for general functional approaches in the spirit of Adamowski, Gerlach, and Leschke. Its entropy term is a configurable quadratic regularizer, not a literature-pinned closed-form Fröhlich action.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.frohlich_feynman_problem","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.frohlich_feynman_problem","text":"frohlich_feynman_problem(; coupling, phonon_frequency=1, dimension=3, ...)\n\nBuild a VariationalProblem{FrohlichModel,GaussianFeynmanTrial}. This is the preferred Fröhlich entry point when using dimensionless coupling/frequency data directly.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.frohlich_multi_gaussian_problem","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.frohlich_multi_gaussian_problem","text":"frohlich_multi_gaussian_problem(; coupling, modes, phonon_frequency=1, dimension=3, ...)\n\nBuild a Fröhlich variational problem using a finite-mode Gaussian trial. The trial parameters are ordered as w1, delta1, w2, delta2, ...; modes = 1 reduces to the Feynman Gaussian trial formulas.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.frohlich_profile_gaussian_problem","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.frohlich_profile_gaussian_problem","text":"frohlich_profile_gaussian_problem(; coupling, basis_frequencies, phonon_frequency=1, dimension=3, ...)\n\nBuild a Fröhlich variational problem using a general Gaussian profile-function trial. The profile is Γ(ω) = sum(aᵢνᵢ² / (ω² + νᵢ²)), with amplitudes optimized by the generic solver.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.frohlich_nonlocal_gaussian_problem","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.frohlich_nonlocal_gaussian_problem","text":"frohlich_nonlocal_gaussian_problem(; coupling, basis_frequencies, phonon_frequency=1, dimension=3, ...)\n\nBuild an experimental Fröhlich variational problem using a finite nonlocal Gaussian kernel basis. The optimized parameters are non-negative amplitudes a1, a2, ...; the entropy term is a configurable quadratic regularizer rather than a literature-pinned closed-form action.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.solve_frohlich","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.solve_frohlich","text":"solve_frohlich(alpha, phonon_frequencies=1; temperatures=[0], frequencies=[0], dimension=3, options=OptimizerOptions())\n\nConvenience wrapper around frohlich_feynman_problem(...) and solve(...). Use the builder-first form when composing with generic solver or sweep tools.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.FrohlichSolution","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.FrohlichSolution","text":"FrohlichSolution\n\nFröhlich-specific optimized solution at one temperature, including Feynman v,w, energy components, effective-mass estimates, and radius diagnostics.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.FrohlichMobilityResult","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.FrohlichMobilityResult","text":"FrohlichMobilityResult\n\nFröhlich DC mobility estimates at one temperature, including memory-function, FHIP, Kadanoff, and Hellwarth references.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.FrohlichResponseResult","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.FrohlichResponseResult","text":"FrohlichResponseResult\n\nFröhlich frequency-dependent memory function, impedance, and conductivity at one temperature/frequency point.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.feynman_v","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.feynman_v","text":"feynman_v(result)\n\nReturn Feynman's v parameter from a Fröhlich VariationalResult or FrohlichSolution.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.feynman_w","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.feynman_w","text":"feynman_w(result)\n\nReturn Feynman's w parameter from a Fröhlich VariationalResult or FrohlichSolution.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.multi_gaussian_v","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.multi_gaussian_v","text":"multi_gaussian_v(result)\n\nReturn all v_i = w_i + delta_i values from a multi-mode Gaussian VariationalResult or FrohlichSolution.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.multi_gaussian_w","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.multi_gaussian_w","text":"multi_gaussian_w(result)\n\nReturn all w_i values from a multi-mode Gaussian VariationalResult or FrohlichSolution.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.mean_square_displacement","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.mean_square_displacement","text":"mean_square_displacement(trial, parameters, tau, beta)\n\nEvaluate the Gaussian trial mean-square-displacement kernel used by Fröhlich interaction integrals. Scalar Feynman, finite-mode Gaussian, and experimental nonlocal Gaussian trials share this extension point.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.profile_function","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.profile_function","text":"profile_function(trial::ProfileGaussianTrial, parameters, omega)\n\nEvaluate the positive Gaussian memory profile Γ(ω) for a ProfileGaussianTrial.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"functions/#Fröhlich-Kernels","page":"API Reference","title":"Fröhlich Kernels","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"functions/","page":"API Reference","title":"API Reference","text":"frohlich_alpha\nfrohlich_energy\nfrohlich_memory_function\nfrohlich_complex_impedance\nfrohlich_complex_conductivity\nfrohlich_mobility\nfhip_low_temperature_mobility\nkadanoff_low_temperature_mobility\nhellwarth_mobility\nhellwarth_b_scheme\nhellwarth_a_scheme","category":"page"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.frohlich_alpha","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.frohlich_alpha","text":"frohlich_alpha(epsilon_optic, epsilon_static, freq_THz, band_mass)\n\nFröhlich coupling for a single LO phonon branch. freq_THz is in THz. Follows the Feynman 1955 convention with the historical 4πϵ₀ normalization.\n\n\n\n\n\nfrohlich_alpha(epsilon_optic, epsilon_ionic, epsilon_ionic_total, freq_THz, band_mass)\n\nPartial Fröhlich coupling for one mode in a multi-phonon decomposition.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.frohlich_energy","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.frohlich_energy","text":"frohlich_energy(v, w, alpha, omega[, beta]; dimension=3)\n\nFeynman/Osaka/Hellwarth variational free energy components. The returned EnergyComponents.total is the variational energy/free energy to minimize.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.frohlich_memory_function","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.frohlich_memory_function","text":"frohlich_memory_function(frequency, v, w, alpha, omega[, beta]; dimension=3, cutoff=1e4, rtol=1e-4)\n\nComplex Fröhlich memory function for Feynman variational parameters v,w. Scalar and multimode alpha, omega inputs are supported.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.frohlich_complex_impedance","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.frohlich_complex_impedance","text":"frohlich_complex_impedance(frequency, v, w, alpha, omega[, beta]; kwargs...)\n\nComplex reduced impedance Z(Ω) = -im * (Ω + Σ(Ω)) from the Fröhlich memory function.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.frohlich_complex_conductivity","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.frohlich_complex_conductivity","text":"frohlich_complex_conductivity(frequency, v, w, alpha, omega[, beta]; kwargs...)\n\nComplex reduced conductivity, defined as the inverse of frohlich_complex_impedance.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.frohlich_mobility","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.frohlich_mobility","text":"frohlich_mobility(v, w, alpha, omega, beta; dimension=3, cutoff=1e4, rtol=1e-4)\n\nReduced DC mobility from the zero-frequency Fröhlich memory function.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.fhip_low_temperature_mobility","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.fhip_low_temperature_mobility","text":"fhip_low_temperature_mobility(v, w, alpha, omega, beta)\n\nLow-temperature FHIP reduced mobility reference for Feynman variational parameters.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.kadanoff_low_temperature_mobility","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.kadanoff_low_temperature_mobility","text":"kadanoff_low_temperature_mobility(v, w, alpha, omega, beta)\n\nLow-temperature Kadanoff mobility references. Returns (devreese_mobility, kadanoff_mobility, relaxation_time).\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.hellwarth_mobility","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.hellwarth_mobility","text":"hellwarth_mobility(v, w, alpha, omega, beta; rtol=1e-3)\n\nHellwarth finite-temperature reduced mobility. Returns (full, b0) where b0 is the simplified b = 0 comparison value.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.hellwarth_b_scheme","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.hellwarth_b_scheme","text":"hellwarth_b_scheme(modes)\n\nHellwarth et al. 1999 PRB B-scheme effective frequency for a matrix whose first column is LO phonon frequency and second column is infrared activity.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.hellwarth_a_scheme","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.hellwarth_a_scheme","text":"hellwarth_a_scheme(modes; temperature=295, convergence=1e-6)\n\nTemperature-dependent Hellwarth et al. 1999 PRB A-scheme effective frequency.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"functions/#Holstein","page":"API Reference","title":"Holstein","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"functions/","page":"API Reference","title":"API Reference","text":"HolsteinModel\nPoissonTrial\nholstein_poisson_problem\nsolve_holstein\nLatticeSolution\nLatticeMobilityResult\nLatticeResponseResult\nreturn_probability","category":"page"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.HolsteinModel","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.HolsteinModel","text":"HolsteinModel(; dimension=1, hopping=1, phonon_frequency=1, coupling)\n\nDimensionless Holstein model with local coupling, bare nearest-neighbor hopping, and Einstein phonon frequency. effective_frequency stores the physical reference frequency in THz when the model is derived from a HolsteinMaterial.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.PoissonTrial","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.PoissonTrial","text":"PoissonTrial(; dimension=1, bare_hopping=1, lower_rate=1e-12, upper_rate=max(10bare_hopping, 1))\n\nContinuous-time symmetric nearest-neighbor hopping trial process for a Holstein polaron on a hypercubic lattice. The single variational parameter is rate.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.holstein_poisson_problem","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.holstein_poisson_problem","text":"holstein_poisson_problem(; hopping=1, phonon_frequency=1, coupling, dimension=1)\n\nBuild a Holstein variational problem using a Poisson hopping trial process. The result can be passed to solve_variational for a single inverse temperature or to solve for temperature/frequency grids. Material-derived problems pass physical Kelvin/THz grids through effective_frequency and material.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.solve_holstein","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.solve_holstein","text":"solve_holstein(; hopping=1, phonon_frequency=1, coupling, dimension=1, temperatures=[1], frequencies=[0])\n\nConvenience wrapper around holstein_poisson_problem(...) and solve(...).\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.LatticeSolution","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.LatticeSolution","text":"LatticeSolution\n\nOptimized Poisson variational solution for lattice polaron models at one temperature.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.LatticeMobilityResult","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.LatticeMobilityResult","text":"LatticeMobilityResult\n\nReduced DC transport result for optimized lattice Poisson trials. mobility stores the transport-corrected lattice mobility, mobility_einstein keeps the bare Einstein estimate, and mobility_factor = mobility / mobility_einstein stores the reduced CTMC transport kernel at zero frequency for finite temperature. diagnostics records transport-specific metadata such as broadening, sideband normalization, and rate provenance.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.LatticeResponseResult","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.LatticeResponseResult","text":"LatticeResponseResult\n\nReduced lattice response for Holstein, Peierls, and compatible composite lattice Poisson models. mobility_factor stores the finite-frequency reduced CTMC transport kernel. At finite temperature the package reports mobility = conductivity = βκ * mobility_factor; at zero temperature and finite frequency it instead reports the reduced optical kernel directly, mobility = conductivity = mobility_factor, avoiding the divergent Einstein prefactor. impedance is always the inverse reduced conductivity. diagnostics records transport-specific metadata such as broadening, sideband normalization, and rate provenance.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.return_probability","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.return_probability","text":"return_probability(trial::PoissonTrial, tau, parameters)\n\nReturn probability of the optimized symmetric Poisson walk at imaginary time tau. Uses the exponentially-scaled Bessel function representation for numerical stability.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"functions/#Lattice-Kernels-And-Mobility-Response","page":"API Reference","title":"Lattice Kernels And Mobility Response","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"functions/","page":"API Reference","title":"API Reference","text":"periodic_phonon_kernel\nlattice_q0\nlattice_q1\nlattice_current_kernel\nsite_return_bridge\nbond_order_bridge\nbond_current_bridge\nholstein_integral_d\npeierls_integral_d\nlattice_green_function_d\nfirst_return_laplace_d\nlattice_holstein_phonon_factor\nlattice_peierls_phonon_factor\nholstein_transport_sidebands\npeierls_transport_sidebands\nholstein_peierls_transport_sidebands\nlattice_mobility_factor\nlattice_mobility\nlattice_conductivity\nlattice_impedance","category":"page"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.periodic_phonon_kernel","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.periodic_phonon_kernel","text":"periodic_phonon_kernel(u, beta, omega)\n\nPeriodic imaginary-time Einstein phonon kernel Dβ(u;ω) = (exp(-ωu) + exp(-ω(β-u))) / (1 - exp(-βω)) for 0 <= u <= beta. For beta == Inf, this reduces to exp(-ωu).\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.lattice_q0","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.lattice_q0","text":"lattice_q0(rate, dimension, tau)\n\nReturn the origin-return probability for a symmetric continuous-time Poisson walk on a dimension-dimensional hypercubic lattice at imaginary time tau. The scaled Bessel representation evaluates [exp(-2κτ) I₀(2κτ)]^d stably.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.lattice_q1","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.lattice_q1","text":"lattice_q1(rate, dimension, tau)\n\nNearest-neighbor displacement probability along one oriented lattice direction for the symmetric CTMC walk, evaluated as exp(-2κτ) I₁(2κτ) [exp(-2κτ) I₀(2κτ)]^(d-1).\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.lattice_current_kernel","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.lattice_current_kernel","text":"lattice_current_kernel(rate, dimension, time)\n\nNormalized open-path CTMC bond-current kernel used by the lattice-FHIP mobility formulas. In reduced units Mκ(t) = 2d κ [q0(t) - q1(t)], whose integral is exactly one.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.site_return_bridge","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.site_return_bridge","text":"site_return_bridge(rate, dimension, u, beta)\n\nCTMC bridge site autocorrelation on a periodic imaginary-time loop. In the large-beta limit it approaches lattice_q0(rate, dimension, u).\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.bond_order_bridge","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.bond_order_bridge","text":"bond_order_bridge(rate, dimension, u, beta)\n\nPeriodic CTMC bridge approximation to a bond-order autocorrelation. Its infinite-beta limit is 2d * (q0(u) + q1(u)), the local bond-order weight used by the full-periodic Peierls free energy.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.bond_current_bridge","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.bond_current_bridge","text":"bond_current_bridge(rate, dimension, u, beta)\n\nPeriodic CTMC bridge approximation to a directed bond-current autocorrelation. The infinite-beta limit is 2d * (q0(u) - q1(u)).\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.holstein_integral_d","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.holstein_integral_d","text":"holstein_integral_d(rate, dimension, omega; laguerre_points=120)\n\nZero-temperature Holstein CTMC influence integral ∫₀∞ exp(-ω t) ive0(2κt)^d dt. For d = 1 this reduces to 1 / sqrt(ω(ω + 4κ)); for d = 2 the square-lattice Green's function gives an elliptic-integral closed form; for d = 3 the cubic-lattice Green's function is reduced to a single finite-interval quadrature over that d = 2 kernel.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.peierls_integral_d","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.peierls_integral_d","text":"peierls_integral_d(rate, dimension, omega; laguerre_points=120)\n\nZero-temperature Peierls bond integral ∫₀∞ exp(-ω t) 2d [ive0(2κt) + ive1(2κt)] ive0(2κt)^(d-1) dt. Rather than integrating this directly, the implementation rewrites it as 2d (G₀ + G_a) using the origin and nearest-neighbor lattice Green's functions.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.lattice_green_function_d","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.lattice_green_function_d","text":"lattice_green_function_d(s, rate, dimension; laguerre_points=120)\n\nGeneral-d CTMC return Green's function G₀^(d)(s) = ∫₀∞ exp(-s t) ive0(2κt)^d dt, evaluated on the retarded sheet for real(s) > 0. For d = 1 an analytic expression is used, for d = 2 the square-lattice Green's function is expressed through the complete elliptic integral K, and for d = 3 the cubic-lattice Green's function is reduced to a single finite-interval quadrature over the d = 2 kernel.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.first_return_laplace_d","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.first_return_laplace_d","text":"first_return_laplace_d(s, rate, dimension; laguerre_points=120)\n\nGeneral-d CTMC first-return kernel (s + 2dκ - 1/G₀^(d)(s)) / (2dκ). For d = 1, this reduces to the closed analytic first-return Laplace transform.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.lattice_holstein_phonon_factor","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.lattice_holstein_phonon_factor","text":"lattice_holstein_phonon_factor(model, beta, time)\n\nExact-cloud Holstein blip factor exp[-S Cβ (1-cos(ω₀ t)) + i S sin(ω₀ t)], where S = 2(g/ω₀)^2.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.lattice_peierls_phonon_factor","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.lattice_peierls_phonon_factor","text":"lattice_peierls_phonon_factor(model, rate, beta, time; response_hopping=:bare)\n\nNormalized Peierls current-vertex cloud (J² + α² D⁾(t)) / (J² + α² D⁾(0)), where J is the selected response hopping scale.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.holstein_transport_sidebands","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.holstein_transport_sidebands","text":"holstein_transport_sidebands(model, beta; tolerance=1e-12)\n\nBuild the exact-cloud Holstein transport sidebands used by the general-d CTMC conductivity and mobility kernels.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.peierls_transport_sidebands","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.peierls_transport_sidebands","text":"peierls_transport_sidebands(model, beta; response_hopping=:bare, tolerance=1e-12)\n\nBuild the normalized Peierls current-vertex sidebands: one zero-phonon channel and finite-temperature ±ωP assisted channels.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.holstein_peierls_transport_sidebands","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.holstein_peierls_transport_sidebands","text":"holstein_peierls_transport_sidebands(model, beta; response_hopping=:bare, tolerance=1e-12)\n\nBuild the composite Holstein-Peierls transport sidebands by convolving the independent Holstein cloud ladder with the Peierls current-vertex channels.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.lattice_mobility_factor","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.lattice_mobility_factor","text":"lattice_mobility_factor(model, rate, beta, frequency; kwargs...)\n\nDimensionless lattice transport kernel μ(Ω) / μE, evaluated from the CTMC first-return kernel and model-specific transport sidebands.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.lattice_mobility","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.lattice_mobility","text":"lattice_mobility(model, rate, beta, frequency; kwargs...)\n\nReduced per-carrier lattice mobility for Holstein, Peierls, or compatible composite lattice models evaluated at Poisson rate rate.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.lattice_conductivity","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.lattice_conductivity","text":"lattice_conductivity(mobility)\n\nReduced per-carrier lattice conductivity. In the reduced convention it is identical to the reduced mobility.\n\n\n\n\n\nlattice_conductivity(model, rate, beta, frequency; kwargs...)\n\nReduced per-carrier lattice conductivity. In the reduced convention this is equal to lattice_mobility(...).\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.lattice_impedance","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.lattice_impedance","text":"lattice_impedance(mobility)\n\nReduced lattice impedance corresponding to a reduced per-carrier mobility or conductivity. In the reduced convention σ(Ω) = μ(Ω) and Z(Ω) = 1 / μ(Ω).\n\n\n\n\n\nlattice_impedance(model, rate, beta, frequency; kwargs...)\n\nReduced lattice impedance corresponding to the CTMC conductivity kernel.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"functions/#Peierls-And-Composite-Lattice-Models","page":"API Reference","title":"Peierls And Composite Lattice Models","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"functions/","page":"API Reference","title":"API Reference","text":"PeierlsModel\nCompositePolaronModel\nPeierlsMaterial\npeierls_poisson_problem\nsolve_peierls\ncombine_models\nlambda_peierls\nrubrene_peierls_material\nrubrene_holstein_peierls_problem","category":"page"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.PeierlsModel","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.PeierlsModel","text":"PeierlsModel(; dimension=1, hopping=1, phonon_frequency=1, coupling)\n\nDimensionless Peierls lattice model with bond-modulation coupling, bare nearest-neighbor hopping, and Einstein bond phonon frequency. The Peierls coupling acts on hopping/bond operators rather than site density.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.CompositePolaronModel","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.CompositePolaronModel","text":"CompositePolaronModel(models...)\n\nCompatible polaron models that share one path/trial space. In this pass, composition is intended for lattice CTMC models such as Holstein plus Peierls with a common PoissonTrial.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.PeierlsMaterial","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.PeierlsMaterial","text":"PeierlsMaterial(...)\n\nOrganic/lattice material metadata for a reduced Peierls bond-coupled model. Constructors derive reduced hopping, phonon frequency, and bond-modulation coupling from transfer integrals, phonon wavenumbers, and Peierls relaxation energies at the API boundary.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.peierls_poisson_problem","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.peierls_poisson_problem","text":"peierls_poisson_problem(; hopping=1, phonon_frequency=1, coupling, dimension=1)\n\nBuild a Peierls variational problem using the same symmetric Poisson hopping trial used by the Holstein lattice model. The Peierls coupling modulates bonds instead of site density.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.solve_peierls","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.solve_peierls","text":"solve_peierls(; hopping=1, phonon_frequency=1, coupling, dimension=1, temperatures=[1], frequencies=[0])\n\nConvenience wrapper around peierls_poisson_problem(...) and solve(...).\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.combine_models","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.combine_models","text":"combine_models(models...)\n\nCombine compatible lattice polaron models so they share one PoissonTrial. The v1 composition path supports Holstein and Peierls components with the same dimension and reduced hopping. Continuum Fröhlich/Gaussian models deliberately cannot be combined with lattice Poisson models.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.lambda_peierls","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.lambda_peierls","text":"lambda_peierls(material)\n\nDimensionless Peierls coupling ratio λ_P = E_P / (2 d J) for a PeierlsMaterial.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.rubrene_peierls_material","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.rubrene_peierls_material","text":"rubrene_peierls_material(; direction=:high_mobility, dimension=1, lattice_constant_angstrom=nothing)\n\nReturn a one-mode Peierls material parameterization for rubrene from Ordejón et al., Phys. Rev. B 96, 035202 (2017), Table II defaults J = 134.0 meV, E_P = 21.9 meV, and ω_P = 117.9 cm^-1.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.rubrene_holstein_peierls_problem","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.rubrene_holstein_peierls_problem","text":"rubrene_holstein_peierls_problem(; direction=:high_mobility, dimension=1, lattice_constant_angstrom=nothing)\n\nBuild a combined rubrene Holstein + Peierls Poisson variational problem using Ordejón Table II defaults. The component models are reduced to one shared Holstein phonon reference frequency before composition, so Kelvin and THz inputs to solve remain unambiguous.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"functions/#Materials-And-Units","page":"API Reference","title":"Materials And Units","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"functions/","page":"API Reference","title":"API Reference","text":"FrohlichMaterial\nHolsteinMaterial\nmaterial_to_problem\nMaterialUnits\nFrohlichResultUnits\nLatticeResultUnits\nmaterial_units\nmobility_cm2_per_v_s\nlattice_mobility_cm2_per_v_s\nenergy_meV\nfrequency_THz\nwavenumber_THz\nwavenumber_meV\nradius_angstrom\nlambda_holstein\nrubrene_holstein_material\ndielectric_ionic_mode\ndielectric_ionic_total","category":"page"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.FrohlichMaterial","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.FrohlichMaterial","text":"FrohlichMaterial(...)\n\nPolar material metadata and dimensionless Fröhlich coupling data. Constructors derive mode couplings from dielectric data at the Unitful boundary.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.HolsteinMaterial","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.HolsteinMaterial","text":"HolsteinMaterial(...)\n\nOrganic/lattice material metadata for a reduced Holstein model. Constructors derive dimensionless hopping and local coupling from transfer integrals, phonon wavenumbers, and local relaxation energies at the API boundary.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.material_to_problem","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.material_to_problem","text":"material_to_problem(material::FrohlichMaterial; dimension=3, trial=:feynman, kwargs...)\n\nConvert a FrohlichMaterial into a reduced-unit Fröhlich VariationalProblem. Pass Kelvin temperatures and THz frequencies directly to solve.\n\ntrial may be :feynman, :multi_gaussian, :profile_gaussian, or :nonlocal_gaussian. Profile and nonlocal trials use the material's reduced phonon frequencies as their default basis frequencies.\n\n\n\n\n\nmaterial_to_problem(material::HolsteinMaterial; trial=:poisson, dimension=material.dimension)\n\nConvert a HolsteinMaterial into a reduced-unit Holstein-Poisson VariationalProblem. Pass Kelvin temperatures and THz frequencies directly to solve; they are reduced using the material phonon frequency.\n\n\n\n\n\nmaterial_to_problem(material::PeierlsMaterial; trial=:poisson, dimension=material.dimension)\n\nConvert a PeierlsMaterial into a reduced-unit Peierls-Poisson VariationalProblem. Pass Kelvin temperatures and THz frequencies directly to solve; they are reduced using the material Peierls phonon frequency.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.MaterialUnits","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.MaterialUnits","text":"MaterialUnits(;)\n\nDefault Unitful output units for material-derived Fröhlich results: THz, cm^2/V/s, meV, and Å.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.FrohlichResultUnits","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.FrohlichResultUnits","text":"FrohlichResultUnits\n\nUnitful arrays converted from a dimensionless continuum PolaronResult by material_units.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.LatticeResultUnits","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.LatticeResultUnits","text":"LatticeResultUnits\n\nUnitful arrays converted from a material-derived lattice PolaronResult by material_units. Mobilities require a lattice constant because the lattice mobility scale is e a^2 / ħ.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.material_units","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.material_units","text":"material_units(result::PolaronResult; units=MaterialUnits())\n\nReturn Unitful mobility, energy, radius, and frequency arrays for a material derived Fröhlich result without mutating the original dimensionless result.\n\n\n\n\n\nmaterial_units(result::PolaronResult; units=MaterialUnits())\n\nReturn Unitful lattice mobilities, solution energies, and response frequencies for a material-derived Holstein result. A lattice constant is required because the mobility conversion uses the lattice scale e a^2 / ħ.\n\n\n\n\n\nmaterial_units(result::PolaronResult; units=MaterialUnits())\n\nReturn Unitful lattice mobilities, solution energies, and response frequencies for material-derived Peierls or compatible composite lattice results. A lattice constant is required for mobility conversion.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.mobility_cm2_per_v_s","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.mobility_cm2_per_v_s","text":"mobility_cm2_per_v_s(mobility, frequency_THz, band_mass)\n\nConvert reduced mobility to cm^2 V^-1 s^-1 using the reference phonon frequency and carrier band mass in electron-mass units.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.lattice_mobility_cm2_per_v_s","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.lattice_mobility_cm2_per_v_s","text":"lattice_mobility_cm2_per_v_s(mobility, lattice_constant_angstrom)\n\nConvert reduced lattice mobility to cm^2 V^-1 s^-1 for a lattice spacing in Å. The scale follows from μ = μ̃ e a^2 / ħ.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.energy_meV","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.energy_meV","text":"energy_meV(energy, frequency_THz)\n\nConvert reduced energy to meV using a reference phonon frequency in THz.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.frequency_THz","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.frequency_THz","text":"frequency_THz(frequency, reference_frequency_THz)\n\nConvert a reduced frequency to THz.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.wavenumber_THz","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.wavenumber_THz","text":"wavenumber_THz(frequency_cm1)\n\nConvert a phonon wavenumber in cm^-1 to cycles-per-second THz.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.wavenumber_meV","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.wavenumber_meV","text":"wavenumber_meV(frequency_cm1)\n\nConvert a phonon wavenumber in cm^-1 to meV.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.radius_angstrom","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.radius_angstrom","text":"radius_angstrom(radius, frequency_THz, band_mass)\n\nConvert a reduced polaron radius to Å using the reference phonon frequency and carrier band mass in electron-mass units.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.lambda_holstein","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.lambda_holstein","text":"lambda_holstein(material)\n\nDimensionless Holstein coupling ratio λ = E_H / (2 d J) for a HolsteinMaterial.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.rubrene_holstein_material","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.rubrene_holstein_material","text":"rubrene_holstein_material(; direction=:high_mobility, dimension=1, lattice_constant_angstrom=nothing)\n\nReturn a one-mode Holstein material parameterization for rubrene from Ordejón et al., Phys. Rev. B 96, 035202 (2017), Table II. The local-coupling defaults are E_H = 106.8 meV and ω_H = 1208.9 cm^-1.\n\ndirection selects the transfer integral magnitude: :high_mobility or :AA_plus_b uses 134.0 meV, :AC uses 28.9 meV, :AB uses 4.1 meV, and :AA_plus_2b uses 10.7 meV.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.dielectric_ionic_mode","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.dielectric_ionic_mode","text":"dielectric_ionic_mode(freq_THz, infrared_activity, volume_m3)\n\nIonic dielectric contribution of one infrared-active phonon mode.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.dielectric_ionic_total","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.dielectric_ionic_total","text":"dielectric_ionic_total(modes, volume_m3)\n\nSum ionic dielectric contributions for a mode matrix whose first column is frequency in THz and second column is infrared activity.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"functions/#Sweeps,-Tables,-And-Plotting","page":"API Reference","title":"Sweeps, Tables, And Plotting","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"functions/","page":"API Reference","title":"API Reference","text":"frequency_sweep\nfrohlich_frequency_sweep\nholstein_frequency_sweep\npeierls_frequency_sweep\nlattice_transport_sweep\nholstein_transport_sweep\npeierls_transport_sweep\nholstein_peierls_transport_sweep\ncontinued_frohlich_temperature_sweep\ncontinued_frohlich_coupling_sweep\ncontinued_frohlich_adiabaticity_sweep\ncontinued_holstein_temperature_sweep\ncontinued_holstein_coupling_sweep\ncontinued_holstein_adiabaticity_sweep\ncontinued_peierls_temperature_sweep\ncontinued_peierls_coupling_sweep\ncontinued_peierls_adiabaticity_sweep\nsolution_table\nmobility_table\nresponse_table\nsweep_table\nwrite_sweep_csv\nplot_coupling_sweep\nplot_temperature_sweep\nplot_adiabaticity_sweep\nplot_frequency_sweep\nplot_response_components","category":"page"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.frequency_sweep","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.frequency_sweep","text":"frequency_sweep(problem; temperatures, frequencies, options=OptimizerOptions())\n\nSolve a variational problem once per temperature and evaluate all requested frequencies without reoptimizing per frequency. Returns flat response rows.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.frohlich_frequency_sweep","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.frohlich_frequency_sweep","text":"frohlich_frequency_sweep(frequencies; coupling, phonon_frequency=1, temperatures=[0], dimension=3, options=OptimizerOptions())\n\nConvenience wrapper for frequency_sweep(frohlich_feynman_problem(...)).\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.holstein_frequency_sweep","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.holstein_frequency_sweep","text":"holstein_frequency_sweep(frequencies; coupling, hopping=1, phonon_frequency=1, temperatures=[1], dimension=1, options=OptimizerOptions())\n\nConvenience wrapper for frequency_sweep(holstein_poisson_problem(...)).\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.peierls_frequency_sweep","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.peierls_frequency_sweep","text":"peierls_frequency_sweep(frequencies; coupling, hopping=1, phonon_frequency=1, temperatures=[1], dimension=1, options=OptimizerOptions())\n\nConvenience wrapper for frequency_sweep(peierls_poisson_problem(...)).\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.lattice_transport_sweep","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.lattice_transport_sweep","text":"lattice_transport_sweep(problem; temperatures, frequencies=[0], options=OptimizerOptions(), kappa_source=:zero_temperature, broadening=1e-6, sideband_tolerance=1e-12, laguerre_points=120)\n\nEvaluate guide-style lattice CTMC transport rows for a Holstein, Peierls, or compatible composite Poisson problem. When kappa_source = :zero_temperature, the transport kernel reuses a single beta = Inf optimized rate across the entire temperature/frequency grid and caches repeated first-return evaluations.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.holstein_transport_sweep","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.holstein_transport_sweep","text":"holstein_transport_sweep(; coupling, hopping=1, phonon_frequency=1, dimension=1, temperatures, frequencies=[0], ...)\n\nConvenience wrapper for guide-style Holstein lattice transport sweeps.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.peierls_transport_sweep","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.peierls_transport_sweep","text":"peierls_transport_sweep(; coupling, hopping=1, phonon_frequency=1, dimension=1, temperatures, frequencies=[0], ...)\n\nConvenience wrapper for guide-style Peierls lattice transport sweeps.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.holstein_peierls_transport_sweep","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.holstein_peierls_transport_sweep","text":"holstein_peierls_transport_sweep(; holstein_coupling, peierls_coupling, hopping=1, holstein_frequency=1, peierls_frequency=1, dimension=1, temperatures, frequencies=[0], ...)\n\nGuide-style transport sweep for a composite Holstein-Peierls model with a shared Poisson trial.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.continued_frohlich_temperature_sweep","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.continued_frohlich_temperature_sweep","text":"continued_frohlich_temperature_sweep(temperatures; coupling, phonon_frequency=1, dimension=3, options=OptimizerOptions())\n\nRun forward and backward warm-started Fröhlich temperature continuations and select the lower-free-energy branch at each point.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.continued_frohlich_coupling_sweep","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.continued_frohlich_coupling_sweep","text":"continued_frohlich_coupling_sweep(couplings; phonon_frequency=1, temperature, dimension=3, options=OptimizerOptions())\n\nRun a Fröhlich coupling continuation at fixed reduced temperature.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.continued_frohlich_adiabaticity_sweep","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.continued_frohlich_adiabaticity_sweep","text":"continued_frohlich_adiabaticity_sweep(adiabatic_ratios; coupling, temperature, dimension=3, options=OptimizerOptions())\n\nRun a Fröhlich adiabaticity continuation where adiabatic_ratio = 1 / phonon_frequency.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.continued_holstein_temperature_sweep","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.continued_holstein_temperature_sweep","text":"continued_holstein_temperature_sweep(temperatures; hopping=1, phonon_frequency=1, coupling, dimension=1, options=OptimizerOptions())\n\nRun forward and backward Holstein temperature continuations and select the lower-free-energy branch at each point.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.continued_holstein_coupling_sweep","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.continued_holstein_coupling_sweep","text":"continued_holstein_coupling_sweep(couplings; hopping=1, phonon_frequency=1, temperature, dimension=1, options=OptimizerOptions())\n\nRun a Holstein coupling continuation at fixed reduced temperature.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.continued_holstein_adiabaticity_sweep","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.continued_holstein_adiabaticity_sweep","text":"continued_holstein_adiabaticity_sweep(adiabatic_ratios; hopping=1, coupling, temperature, dimension=1, options=OptimizerOptions())\n\nRun a Holstein adiabaticity continuation where adiabatic_ratio = hopping / phonon_frequency.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.continued_peierls_temperature_sweep","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.continued_peierls_temperature_sweep","text":"continued_peierls_temperature_sweep(temperatures; hopping=1, phonon_frequency=1, coupling, dimension=1, options=OptimizerOptions())\n\nRun forward and backward Peierls temperature continuations and select the lower-free-energy branch at each point.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.continued_peierls_coupling_sweep","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.continued_peierls_coupling_sweep","text":"continued_peierls_coupling_sweep(couplings; hopping=1, phonon_frequency=1, temperature, dimension=1, options=OptimizerOptions())\n\nRun a Peierls coupling continuation at fixed reduced temperature.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.continued_peierls_adiabaticity_sweep","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.continued_peierls_adiabaticity_sweep","text":"continued_peierls_adiabaticity_sweep(adiabatic_ratios; hopping=1, coupling, temperature, dimension=1, options=OptimizerOptions())\n\nRun a Peierls adiabaticity continuation where adiabatic_ratio = hopping / phonon_frequency.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.solution_table","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.solution_table","text":"solution_table(result)\n\nReturn flat NamedTuple rows for optimized variational solutions in a PolaronResult.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.mobility_table","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.mobility_table","text":"mobility_table(result)\n\nReturn flat NamedTuple rows for DC mobility observables in a PolaronResult.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.response_table","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.response_table","text":"response_table(result)\n\nReturn flat NamedTuple rows for frequency-dependent response observables in a PolaronResult.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.sweep_table","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.sweep_table","text":"sweep_table(result_or_rows)\n\nNormalize a result or existing row vector to flat sweep rows. For solve results this returns response_table(result), which includes solution parameters at each temperature/frequency point.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.write_sweep_csv","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.write_sweep_csv","text":"write_sweep_csv(path, rows)\n\nWrite flat sweep/table rows to a comma-separated file without adding a plotting or table dependency. Returns path.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.plot_coupling_sweep","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.plot_coupling_sweep","text":"plot_coupling_sweep(rows; kwargs...)\n\nPlot coupling-sweep rows. Load a plotting backend extension, such as Plots.jl, to enable this function.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.plot_temperature_sweep","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.plot_temperature_sweep","text":"plot_temperature_sweep(rows; kwargs...)\n\nPlot temperature-sweep rows. Load a plotting backend extension, such as Plots.jl, to enable this function.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.plot_adiabaticity_sweep","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.plot_adiabaticity_sweep","text":"plot_adiabaticity_sweep(rows; kwargs...)\n\nPlot adiabaticity-sweep rows. Load a plotting backend extension, such as Plots.jl, to enable this function.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.plot_frequency_sweep","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.plot_frequency_sweep","text":"plot_frequency_sweep(rows; kwargs...)\n\nPlot frequency-sweep rows. Load a plotting backend extension, such as Plots.jl, to enable this function.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"functions/#PolaronMobility.plot_response_components","page":"API Reference","title":"PolaronMobility.plot_response_components","text":"plot_response_components(rows; kwargs...)\n\nPlot frequency-response components such as mobility factor, conductivity, impedance, or continuum memory-function observables. Load a plotting backend extension to enable this function.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"examples/#Examples","page":"Examples","title":"Examples","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"examples/","page":"Examples","title":"Examples","text":"The scripts in examples/*.jl are executable demos and are also run by the test suite as smoke tests. They are intentionally compact, but together they exercise the package's main workflows.","category":"page"},{"location":"examples/#Fröhlich-Basic-Workflow","page":"Examples","title":"Fröhlich Basic Workflow","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"examples/","page":"Examples","title":"Examples","text":"Run:","category":"page"},{"location":"examples/","page":"Examples","title":"Examples","text":"include(\"examples/frohlich_basic.jl\")","category":"page"},{"location":"examples/","page":"Examples","title":"Examples","text":"This demonstrates:","category":"page"},{"location":"examples/","page":"Examples","title":"Examples","text":"Building frohlich_feynman_problem.\nSolving zero and finite reduced temperatures.\nReading optimized v,w, mobility, memory function, impedance, and conductivity.\nCalling solve_variational directly for a single inverse temperature.\nFlattening typed results with solution_table, mobility_table, and response_table.","category":"page"},{"location":"examples/","page":"Examples","title":"Examples","text":"The core pattern is:","category":"page"},{"location":"examples/","page":"Examples","title":"Examples","text":"problem = frohlich_feynman_problem(coupling = 3.0)\nresult = solve(problem; temperatures = [0.0, 0.5], frequencies = [0.0, 1.0])","category":"page"},{"location":"examples/#Fröhlich-Trial-Families","page":"Examples","title":"Fröhlich Trial Families","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"examples/","page":"Examples","title":"Examples","text":"Run:","category":"page"},{"location":"examples/","page":"Examples","title":"Examples","text":"include(\"examples/frohlich_trials.jl\")","category":"page"},{"location":"examples/","page":"Examples","title":"Examples","text":"This compares:","category":"page"},{"location":"examples/","page":"Examples","title":"Examples","text":"GaussianFeynmanTrial: the one-fictitious-oscillator production path.\nMultiGaussianTrial: several fictitious oscillator modes.\nProfileGaussianTrial: a positive profile-function Gaussian trial.\nNonlocalGaussianTrial: an experimental finite-basis kernel scaffold.","category":"page"},{"location":"examples/","page":"Examples","title":"Examples","text":"The profile trial is useful because it contains the Feynman trial as a special case. If Feynman's optimized parameters are v,w, then","category":"page"},{"location":"examples/","page":"Examples","title":"Examples","text":"Gamma_F(omega) = fracv^2-w^2omega^2+w^2","category":"page"},{"location":"examples/","page":"Examples","title":"Examples","text":"is represented by a one-basis profile with basis_frequencies = [w] and a1 = (v^2 - w^2)/w^2. The example prints this embedding as a sanity check.","category":"page"},{"location":"examples/","page":"Examples","title":"Examples","text":"A more general profile calculation looks like:","category":"page"},{"location":"examples/","page":"Examples","title":"Examples","text":"problem = frohlich_profile_gaussian_problem(\n    coupling = 2.0,\n    basis_frequencies = [0.75, 1.5],\n    matsubara_terms = 128,\n)","category":"page"},{"location":"examples/","page":"Examples","title":"Examples","text":"profile_function(trial, parameters, omega) and mean_square_displacement(trial, parameters, tau, beta) are exported so the kernel itself can be inspected.","category":"page"},{"location":"examples/","page":"Examples","title":"Examples","text":"NonlocalGaussianTrial is intentionally not shown as a validated lower-energy variational improvement. It uses a regularized kernel objective rather than the profile log-determinant entropy, so its pseudo-objective is not directly comparable to Feynman or profile variational energies.","category":"page"},{"location":"examples/#Material-Workflows","page":"Examples","title":"Material Workflows","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"examples/","page":"Examples","title":"Examples","text":"Run:","category":"page"},{"location":"examples/","page":"Examples","title":"Examples","text":"include(\"examples/material_workflows.jl\")","category":"page"},{"location":"examples/","page":"Examples","title":"Examples","text":"This demonstrates:","category":"page"},{"location":"examples/","page":"Examples","title":"Examples","text":"Single-mode material construction from dielectric constants, effective mass, and phonon frequency.\nMultimode material construction from phonon frequencies, infrared activities, and cell volume.\nmaterial_to_problem for every Fröhlich trial family.\nRubrene HolsteinMaterial construction from local Holstein parameters.\nRubrene PeierlsMaterial construction from bond-coupling parameters.\nCombined Rubrene Holstein + Peierls composition on one Poisson trial.\nConversion back to common units through material_units.","category":"page"},{"location":"examples/","page":"Examples","title":"Examples","text":"Material-derived problems keep Kelvin and THz at the solve boundary:","category":"page"},{"location":"examples/","page":"Examples","title":"Examples","text":"material = FrohlichMaterial(4.5, 24.1, 0.12, 2.25)\nproblem = material_to_problem(material; trial = :feynman)\nresult = solve(problem; temperatures = [0, 300], frequencies = [0, 3])","category":"page"},{"location":"examples/","page":"Examples","title":"Examples","text":"All Fröhlich trial families can be selected from the same material:","category":"page"},{"location":"examples/","page":"Examples","title":"Examples","text":"material_to_problem(material; trial = :feynman)\nmaterial_to_problem(material; trial = :multi_gaussian, modes = 2)\nmaterial_to_problem(material; trial = :profile_gaussian, matsubara_terms = 256)\nmaterial_to_problem(material; trial = :nonlocal_gaussian)","category":"page"},{"location":"examples/","page":"Examples","title":"Examples","text":"For profile and nonlocal trials, default basis frequencies are the material's reduced phonon frequencies. This means multimode material-derived profile problems solve without manual basis construction.","category":"page"},{"location":"examples/","page":"Examples","title":"Examples","text":"Rubrene can be mapped into the Holstein-Poisson pipeline from the Ordejón et al. local-coupling data:","category":"page"},{"location":"examples/","page":"Examples","title":"Examples","text":"rubrene = rubrene_holstein_material(lattice_constant_angstrom = 7.2)\nproblem = material_to_problem(rubrene)\nresult = solve(problem; temperatures = [300], frequencies = [0, 10])\nunits = material_units(result)","category":"page"},{"location":"examples/","page":"Examples","title":"Examples","text":"The Holstein mapping uses J = 134.0 meV, E_H = 106.8 meV, and ω_H = 1208.9 cm^-1. The Peierls mapping uses the same transfer integral with E_P = 21.9 meV and ω_P = 117.9 cm^-1:","category":"page"},{"location":"examples/","page":"Examples","title":"Examples","text":"rubrene_p = rubrene_peierls_material(lattice_constant_angstrom = 7.2)\nproblem_p = material_to_problem(rubrene_p)\nresult_p = solve(problem_p; temperatures = [300], frequencies = [0, 10])","category":"page"},{"location":"examples/","page":"Examples","title":"Examples","text":"To combine local and bond couplings, use the convenience builder:","category":"page"},{"location":"examples/","page":"Examples","title":"Examples","text":"problem_hp = rubrene_holstein_peierls_problem(lattice_constant_angstrom = 7.2)\nresult_hp = solve(problem_hp; temperatures = [300], frequencies = [0, 10])","category":"page"},{"location":"examples/#Peierls-And-Limits","page":"Examples","title":"Peierls And Limits","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"examples/","page":"Examples","title":"Examples","text":"Run:","category":"page"},{"location":"examples/","page":"Examples","title":"Examples","text":"include(\"examples/peierls_basic.jl\")\ninclude(\"examples/model_limits.jl\")","category":"page"},{"location":"examples/","page":"Examples","title":"Examples","text":"These scripts demonstrate standalone Peierls variational solves, Holstein plus Peierls model composition, and coded limit checks: Fröhlich weak/strong coupling markers, Holstein zero-coupling and high-temperature behavior, Peierls g_P^2 weak-coupling scaling, and adiabatic/antiadiabatic ratios.","category":"page"},{"location":"examples/#Holstein-Basic-Workflow","page":"Examples","title":"Holstein Basic Workflow","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"examples/","page":"Examples","title":"Examples","text":"Run:","category":"page"},{"location":"examples/","page":"Examples","title":"Examples","text":"include(\"examples/holstein_basic.jl\")","category":"page"},{"location":"examples/","page":"Examples","title":"Examples","text":"This demonstrates:","category":"page"},{"location":"examples/","page":"Examples","title":"Examples","text":"Building holstein_poisson_problem.\nOptimizing the CTMC hopping rate.\nReading Einstein and CTMC first-return projected mobilities.\nEvaluating return probabilities.\nEvaluating frequency-dependent complex mobility and mobility factors.","category":"page"},{"location":"examples/","page":"Examples","title":"Examples","text":"The core pattern is:","category":"page"},{"location":"examples/","page":"Examples","title":"Examples","text":"problem = holstein_poisson_problem(coupling = 1.5, hopping = 1.0)\nresult = solve(problem; temperatures = [0.25, 0.5], frequencies = [0.0, 1.0])","category":"page"},{"location":"examples/","page":"Examples","title":"Examples","text":"At zero coupling, the optimized rate returns the bare hopping. Finite coupling adds a full-periodic bridge free-energy correction and a CTMC first-return sideband response through mobility_factor, impedance, conductivity, and mobility fields.","category":"page"},{"location":"examples/#CTMC-Lattice-Transport","page":"Examples","title":"CTMC Lattice Transport","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"examples/","page":"Examples","title":"Examples","text":"Run:","category":"page"},{"location":"examples/","page":"Examples","title":"Examples","text":"include(\"examples/full_lattice_free_energy.jl\")\ninclude(\"examples/lattice_mobility_response.jl\")\ninclude(\"examples/holstein_peierls_mobility_comparison.jl\")\ninclude(\"examples/general_d_lattice_transport.jl\")","category":"page"},{"location":"examples/","page":"Examples","title":"Examples","text":"These scripts demonstrate the active lattice theory: periodic phonon kernels, CTMC site/bond bridge correlations, the general-d CTMC first-return kernel, exact Holstein blip sidebands, Peierls current-vertex sidebands, and Holstein-Peierls sideband convolution.","category":"page"},{"location":"examples/","page":"Examples","title":"Examples","text":"general_d_lattice_transport.jl also demonstrates the guide-style helpers","category":"page"},{"location":"examples/","page":"Examples","title":"Examples","text":"holstein_transport_sweep(...)\npeierls_transport_sweep(...)\nholstein_peierls_transport_sweep(...)","category":"page"},{"location":"examples/","page":"Examples","title":"Examples","text":"which default to kappa_source = :zero_temperature so one optimized zero-temperature rate can be reused across a temperature or frequency study.","category":"page"},{"location":"examples/#Sweeps,-Tables,-CSV,-And-Plotting","page":"Examples","title":"Sweeps, Tables, CSV, And Plotting","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"examples/","page":"Examples","title":"Examples","text":"Run:","category":"page"},{"location":"examples/","page":"Examples","title":"Examples","text":"include(\"examples/sweeps_tables_plots.jl\")","category":"page"},{"location":"examples/","page":"Examples","title":"Examples","text":"This demonstrates:","category":"page"},{"location":"examples/","page":"Examples","title":"Examples","text":"Fröhlich coupling sweeps.\nHolstein temperature sweeps.\nFröhlich and Holstein frequency sweeps.\nCSV export through write_sweep_csv.\nOptional plots through the Plots.jl extension.","category":"page"},{"location":"examples/","page":"Examples","title":"Examples","text":"Frequency sweeps optimize once per temperature and then evaluate every frequency:","category":"page"},{"location":"examples/","page":"Examples","title":"Examples","text":"rows = frohlich_frequency_sweep(\n    [0.0, 0.5, 1.0];\n    coupling = 1.0,\n    temperatures = [0.5],\n)\n\nwrite_sweep_csv(\"frequency.csv\", rows)","category":"page"},{"location":"examples/","page":"Examples","title":"Examples","text":"If Plots.jl is loaded, the plotting extension activates:","category":"page"},{"location":"examples/","page":"Examples","title":"Examples","text":"using Plots\n\nplot_frequency_sweep(rows)\nplot_response_components(rows)","category":"page"},{"location":"examples/","page":"Examples","title":"Examples","text":"The plotting API intentionally consumes flat rows rather than result structs. That keeps the core solver independent from plotting choices and makes CSV, notebook, and batch-report workflows use the same data representation.","category":"page"},{"location":"lattice_transport/#Lattice-Transport-Theory","page":"Lattice Transport","title":"Lattice Transport Theory","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"lattice_transport/","page":"Lattice Transport","title":"Lattice Transport","text":"This page records the active lattice implementation used by HolsteinModel, PeierlsModel, and compatible CompositePolaronModel calculations.","category":"page"},{"location":"lattice_transport/","page":"Lattice Transport","title":"Lattice Transport","text":"There are two related pieces:","category":"page"},{"location":"lattice_transport/","page":"Lattice Transport","title":"Lattice Transport","text":"a CTMC/Feynman-Jensen variational free energy built from periodic bridge correlations; and\na CTMC first-return transport projection dressed by Holstein and Peierls phonon sidebands.","category":"page"},{"location":"lattice_transport/","page":"Lattice Transport","title":"Lattice Transport","text":"The same optimized Poisson hopping rate κ can be used for both, but the two approximations are conceptually distinct. The free energy is a normalized imaginary-time variational calculation. The transport calculation is a current-vertex/blip approximation using the first-return kernel of the CTMC.","category":"page"},{"location":"lattice_transport/#CTMC-Trial-Process","page":"Lattice Transport","title":"CTMC Trial Process","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"lattice_transport/","page":"Lattice Transport","title":"Lattice Transport","text":"The lattice trial is a symmetric continuous-time nearest-neighbor Markov chain with hopping rate κ on a d-dimensional hypercubic lattice. The free trial contribution and relative-entropy mismatch are","category":"page"},{"location":"lattice_transport/","page":"Lattice Transport","title":"Lattice Transport","text":"F_0(kappa)=-2dkappa\nqquad\nS_mathrmrel(kappa)=2dkappalogfrackappaJ","category":"page"},{"location":"lattice_transport/","page":"Lattice Transport","title":"Lattice Transport","text":"The CTMC propagator factorizes as","category":"page"},{"location":"lattice_transport/","page":"Lattice Transport","title":"Lattice Transport","text":"P_mathbf r^(d)(t)=\ne^-2dkappa tprod_mu=1^dI_r_mu(2kappa t)","category":"page"},{"location":"lattice_transport/","page":"Lattice Transport","title":"Lattice Transport","text":"The package uses","category":"page"},{"location":"lattice_transport/","page":"Lattice Transport","title":"Lattice Transport","text":"q_0(t)=lefte^-2kappa tI_0(2kappa t)right^d","category":"page"},{"location":"lattice_transport/","page":"Lattice Transport","title":"Lattice Transport","text":"q_1(t)=e^-2dkappa tI_1(2kappa t)I_0(2kappa t)^d-1","category":"page"},{"location":"lattice_transport/","page":"Lattice Transport","title":"Lattice Transport","text":"These are implemented as lattice_q0 and lattice_q1 using exponentially scaled Bessel functions.","category":"page"},{"location":"lattice_transport/#Periodic-Bridge-Free-Energies","page":"Lattice Transport","title":"Periodic Bridge Free Energies","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"lattice_transport/","page":"Lattice Transport","title":"Lattice Transport","text":"For finite inverse temperature β, the Einstein phonon kernel is","category":"page"},{"location":"lattice_transport/","page":"Lattice Transport","title":"Lattice Transport","text":"D_beta(uomega)=\nfrace^-omega u+e^-omega(beta-u)1-e^-betaomega","category":"page"},{"location":"lattice_transport/","page":"Lattice Transport","title":"Lattice Transport","text":"Holstein uses the site bridge","category":"page"},{"location":"lattice_transport/","page":"Lattice Transport","title":"Lattice Transport","text":"C_mathrmsite(ubeta)=\nfracq_0(u)q_0(beta-u)q_0(beta)","category":"page"},{"location":"lattice_transport/","page":"Lattice Transport","title":"Lattice Transport","text":"The finite-temperature Holstein objective is","category":"page"},{"location":"lattice_transport/","page":"Lattice Transport","title":"Lattice Transport","text":"F_rm var^H(kappabeta)=\n-2dkappa\n+2dkappalogfrackappaJ\n-\nfracg^22\nint_0^beta D_beta(uomega_H)C_rm site(ubeta)du","category":"page"},{"location":"lattice_transport/","page":"Lattice Transport","title":"Lattice Transport","text":"Peierls uses the bond-order bridge","category":"page"},{"location":"lattice_transport/","page":"Lattice Transport","title":"Lattice Transport","text":"C_mathrmbond^+(ubeta)=\n2dfracq_0(u)q_0(beta-u)+q_1(u)q_1(beta-u)q_0(beta)","category":"page"},{"location":"lattice_transport/","page":"Lattice Transport","title":"Lattice Transport","text":"The finite-temperature Peierls interaction contribution is","category":"page"},{"location":"lattice_transport/","page":"Lattice Transport","title":"Lattice Transport","text":"F_P(kappabeta)=\n-fracg_P^22\nint_0^beta D_beta(uomega_P)C_rm bond^+(ubeta)du","category":"page"},{"location":"lattice_transport/","page":"Lattice Transport","title":"Lattice Transport","text":"At zero temperature, the package exposes Laguerre-integral kernels","category":"page"},{"location":"lattice_transport/","page":"Lattice Transport","title":"Lattice Transport","text":"I_H^(d)(kappa)=\nint_0^infty dte^-omega_Htoperatornameive_0(2kappa t)^d","category":"page"},{"location":"lattice_transport/","page":"Lattice Transport","title":"Lattice Transport","text":"I_P^(d)(kappa)=\nint_0^infty dte^-omega_Pt\n2doperatornameive_0(2kappa t)+operatornameive_1(2kappa t)\noperatornameive_0(2kappa t)^d-1","category":"page"},{"location":"lattice_transport/","page":"Lattice Transport","title":"Lattice Transport","text":"Thus","category":"page"},{"location":"lattice_transport/","page":"Lattice Transport","title":"Lattice Transport","text":"F_H(kappainfty)=-g^2I_H^(d)(kappa)\nqquad\nF_P(kappainfty)=-fracg_P^22I_P^(d)(kappa)","category":"page"},{"location":"lattice_transport/","page":"Lattice Transport","title":"Lattice Transport","text":"For a composite Holstein-Peierls model, independent influence functionals are summed on the same Poisson path measure.","category":"page"},{"location":"lattice_transport/#General-d-First-Return-Kernel","page":"Lattice Transport","title":"General-d First-Return Kernel","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"lattice_transport/","page":"Lattice Transport","title":"Lattice Transport","text":"Transport uses the CTMC first-return kernel from a nearest neighbor back to the origin. Let","category":"page"},{"location":"lattice_transport/","page":"Lattice Transport","title":"Lattice Transport","text":"G_0^(d)(s)=\nint_0^infty dte^-stoperatornameive_0(2kappa t)^d\nqquad Re s0","category":"page"},{"location":"lattice_transport/","page":"Lattice Transport","title":"Lattice Transport","text":"Then the lattice resolvent identity gives","category":"page"},{"location":"lattice_transport/","page":"Lattice Transport","title":"Lattice Transport","text":"widehat f_ato0^(d)(s)=\nfracs+2dkappa-G_0^(d)(s)^-12dkappa","category":"page"},{"location":"lattice_transport/","page":"Lattice Transport","title":"Lattice Transport","text":"For d = 1, this reduces to","category":"page"},{"location":"lattice_transport/","page":"Lattice Transport","title":"Lattice Transport","text":"widehat f_1to0^(1)(s)=\nfracs+2kappa-sqrts(s+4kappa)2kappa","category":"page"},{"location":"lattice_transport/","page":"Lattice Transport","title":"Lattice Transport","text":"For d = 2, the package uses the square-lattice elliptic-integral Green's function","category":"page"},{"location":"lattice_transport/","page":"Lattice Transport","title":"Lattice Transport","text":"G_0^(2)(s)=\nfrac2pi(s+4kappa)\nKleftleft(frac4kappas+4kapparight)^2right","category":"page"},{"location":"lattice_transport/","page":"Lattice Transport","title":"Lattice Transport","text":"For d = 3, it uses the cubic-lattice reduction","category":"page"},{"location":"lattice_transport/","page":"Lattice Transport","title":"Lattice Transport","text":"G_0^(3)(s)=\nfrac1piint_0^pi\nG_0^(2)left(s+2kappa(1-cos q)right)dq","category":"page"},{"location":"lattice_transport/","page":"Lattice Transport","title":"Lattice Transport","text":"Only dimensions beyond the standard hypercubic d = 1, 2, 3 path fall back to the generic Bessel/Laplace quadrature. The retarded response uses s = broadening - im * frequency_shift with positive broadening.","category":"page"},{"location":"lattice_transport/#Holstein,-Peierls,-And-Composite-Sidebands","page":"Lattice Transport","title":"Holstein, Peierls, And Composite Sidebands","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"lattice_transport/","page":"Lattice Transport","title":"Lattice Transport","text":"Holstein transport uses the exact-cloud current-blip factor","category":"page"},{"location":"lattice_transport/","page":"Lattice Transport","title":"Lattice Transport","text":"C_H(t)=\nexp-S_H C_beta(1-cosomega_Ht)\nexpiS_Hsinomega_Ht\nqquad\nS_H=2(gomega_H)^2","category":"page"},{"location":"lattice_transport/","page":"Lattice Transport","title":"Lattice Transport","text":"At T = 0, this is a Poisson sideband ladder. At finite temperature, the sidebands are equivalent to the usual Bessel-weighted Holstein cloud expansion.","category":"page"},{"location":"lattice_transport/","page":"Lattice Transport","title":"Lattice Transport","text":"Peierls transport is a current-vertex factor, not a Franck-Condon ladder:","category":"page"},{"location":"lattice_transport/","page":"Lattice Transport","title":"Lattice Transport","text":"mathcal C_P(t)=\nfracJ_rm resp^2+g_P^2D_P^(t)J_rm resp^2+g_P^2D_P^(0)","category":"page"},{"location":"lattice_transport/","page":"Lattice Transport","title":"Lattice Transport","text":"At finite temperature,","category":"page"},{"location":"lattice_transport/","page":"Lattice Transport","title":"Lattice Transport","text":"D_P^(t)=(N_P+1)e^-iomega_Pt+N_Pe^iomega_Pt","category":"page"},{"location":"lattice_transport/","page":"Lattice Transport","title":"Lattice Transport","text":"So Peierls contributes a zero-phonon current channel and ±ω_P assisted channels. J_resp comes from response_hopping, whose default is the bare model hopping.","category":"page"},{"location":"lattice_transport/","page":"Lattice Transport","title":"Lattice Transport","text":"For independent Holstein and Peierls phonons, the composite cloud is","category":"page"},{"location":"lattice_transport/","page":"Lattice Transport","title":"Lattice Transport","text":"C_HP(t)=C_H(t)mathcal C_P(t)","category":"page"},{"location":"lattice_transport/","page":"Lattice Transport","title":"Lattice Transport","text":"so the sidebands are a convolution. Shared-mode cross terms are not included.","category":"page"},{"location":"lattice_transport/#Mobility,-Conductivity,-And-Impedance","page":"Lattice Transport","title":"Mobility, Conductivity, And Impedance","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"lattice_transport/","page":"Lattice Transport","title":"Lattice Transport","text":"The reduced Einstein scale is","category":"page"},{"location":"lattice_transport/","page":"Lattice Transport","title":"Lattice Transport","text":"mu_E=betakappa","category":"page"},{"location":"lattice_transport/","page":"Lattice Transport","title":"Lattice Transport","text":"Given model sidebands (ν_m, w_m), the reduced transport kernel is","category":"page"},{"location":"lattice_transport/","page":"Lattice Transport","title":"Lattice Transport","text":"K(Omega)=\nsum_m w_mwidehat f_ato0^(d)(epsilon-i(Omega+nu_m))","category":"page"},{"location":"lattice_transport/","page":"Lattice Transport","title":"Lattice Transport","text":"The package reports","category":"page"},{"location":"lattice_transport/","page":"Lattice Transport","title":"Lattice Transport","text":"mu(Omega)=mu_EK(Omega)\nqquad\nsigma(Omega)=mu(Omega)\nqquad\nZ(Omega)=sigma(Omega)^-1","category":"page"},{"location":"lattice_transport/","page":"Lattice Transport","title":"Lattice Transport","text":"For T = 0, the DC mobility still diverges, but the finite-frequency optical response is reported in the reduced current-current normalization,","category":"page"},{"location":"lattice_transport/","page":"Lattice Transport","title":"Lattice Transport","text":"mu(Omega)=sigma(Omega)=K(Omega) qquad Omega neq 0 T=0","category":"page"},{"location":"lattice_transport/","page":"Lattice Transport","title":"Lattice Transport","text":"so the Holstein and Peierls optical spectra remain finite while mobility_factor continues to store the same transport kernel.","category":"page"},{"location":"lattice_transport/","page":"Lattice Transport","title":"Lattice Transport","text":"LatticeMobilityResult stores the DC value mobility, the Einstein estimate mobility_einstein, the reduced kernel mobility_factor, and diagnostics such as sideband count, sideband normalization, broadening, Laguerre points, and rate provenance. The same metadata is carried by LatticeResponseResult.","category":"page"},{"location":"lattice_transport/#Guide-Style-Sweeps","page":"Lattice Transport","title":"Guide-Style Sweeps","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"lattice_transport/","page":"Lattice Transport","title":"Lattice Transport","text":"Besides the main solve(...) API, the package exposes","category":"page"},{"location":"lattice_transport/","page":"Lattice Transport","title":"Lattice Transport","text":"lattice_transport_sweep(problem; temperatures, frequencies, kappa_source = :zero_temperature)\nholstein_transport_sweep(...)\npeierls_transport_sweep(...)\nholstein_peierls_transport_sweep(...)","category":"page"},{"location":"lattice_transport/","page":"Lattice Transport","title":"Lattice Transport","text":"These helpers are intended for theory-driven mobility studies:","category":"page"},{"location":"lattice_transport/","page":"Lattice Transport","title":"Lattice Transport","text":"kappa_source = :zero_temperature reuses one frozen β = ∞ optimized rate,\nkappa_source = :per_temperature reoptimizes at every requested temperature,\nsidebands are built over the requested temperature grid,\nrepeated complex first-return evaluations are cached over reused frequency shifts,\nreturned rows include mobility, mobility_factor, conductivity_real, conductivity_imag, conductivity_abs, and transport diagnostics.","category":"page"},{"location":"lattice_transport/","page":"Lattice Transport","title":"Lattice Transport","text":"A typical DC mobility sweep is","category":"page"},{"location":"lattice_transport/","page":"Lattice Transport","title":"Lattice Transport","text":"rows = holstein_peierls_transport_sweep(\n    holstein_coupling = 1.5,\n    peierls_coupling = 0.5,\n    dimension = 3,\n    temperatures = 0.1:0.1:2.0,\n    frequencies = [0.0],\n    kappa_source = :zero_temperature,\n)","category":"page"},{"location":"#PolaronMobility.jl","page":"Home","title":"PolaronMobility.jl","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"PolaronMobility.jl is a Julia package for variational polaron calculations, mobility estimates, and frequency-dependent response. The package is organized around one composable pipeline:","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"problem = VariationalProblem(model, trial)\nresult = solve(problem; temperatures, frequencies)","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"The model describes the electron-phonon Hamiltonian. The trial process is the solvable stochastic process used in the Feynman-Jensen variational objective. The solver optimizes trial parameters on a temperature grid and then evaluates model-specific observables on a frequency grid.","category":"page"},{"location":"#Implemented-Pipelines","page":"Home","title":"Implemented Pipelines","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"FrohlichModel + GaussianFeynmanTrial: the literature-pinned one-mode Feynman path-integral variational polaron.\nFrohlichModel + MultiGaussianTrial: Martin-Frost-style finite fictitious oscillator modes.\nFrohlichModel + ProfileGaussianTrial: a positive profile-function Gaussian trial in the Adamowski, Gerlach, and Leschke functional-integral spirit.\nFrohlichModel + NonlocalGaussianTrial: an experimental nonlocal kernel scaffold for exploratory response calculations.\nHolsteinModel + PoissonTrial: a lattice Holstein polaron trialled by a continuous-time Markov chain (CTMC) hopping process.\nPeierlsModel + PoissonTrial: a standalone bond-coupled Peierls lattice polaron using the same CTMC trial.\nCompositePolaronModel + PoissonTrial: compatible lattice influence functionals, currently Holstein plus Peierls on one Poisson path measure.","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"All core calculations are dimensionless. Unitful conversion is deliberately kept at the API boundary through FrohlichMaterial, HolsteinMaterial, PeierlsMaterial, material_to_problem, and material_units.","category":"page"},{"location":"#The-Shared-Shape","page":"Home","title":"The Shared Shape","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"Fröhlich, Holstein, Peierls, and compatible composite workflows return results with the same top-level fields:","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"result.problem\nresult.temperatures\nresult.frequencies\nresult.solutions\nresult.mobilities\nresult.responses","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"Fröhlich results also expose result.zero_temperature, because the zero-temperature variational solution is the standard literature reference and is useful even when the requested temperature grid starts at finite temperature.","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"The objective minimized by solve_variational(problem, beta) is always","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"free_energy(trial, parameters, beta) +\nentropy_cost(trial, parameters, beta) +\ninteraction_free_energy(model, trial, parameters, beta)","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"This decomposition is the extension contract: a new model/trial pair only needs to define its parameters, bounds, objective terms, and observable hooks.","category":"page"},{"location":"#Stochastic-Process-View","page":"Home","title":"Stochastic Process View","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"The package treats variational trials as probability measures over paths.","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"For Fröhlich polarons, phonons are integrated out to produce a retarded self-interaction of a continuum particle path. Gaussian trials replace the exact path measure by a Gaussian process with a prescribed memory kernel. The original Feynman trial is the one-fictitious-oscillator Gaussian process.","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"For Holstein and Peierls polarons, the electron lives on a lattice. The PoissonTrial replaces the exact lattice path measure by a symmetric CTMC with hopping rate rate. Holstein local phonons generate a retarded attraction between times at which the CTMC returns to the same lattice site. Peierls bond phonons generate a retarded bond-order influence evaluated with the full periodic CTMC bridge.","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"This is why the two models can share the same Julia pipeline even though their path spaces are different: Fröhlich integrates Gaussian displacements, while lattice models integrate CTMC site and bond bridge correlations.","category":"page"},{"location":"#Literature-Map","page":"Home","title":"Literature Map","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"The Fröhlich side follows the older path-integral variational tradition:","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"Fröhlich introduced the continuum polar electron-phonon model.\nFeynman introduced the all-coupling path-integral variational solution.\nSchultz provided early self-energy, mass, and mobility comparisons.\nOsaka extended the variational free energy to finite temperature.\nFeynman, Hellwarth, Iddings, and Platzman (FHIP) built the linear-response mobility theory around Feynman's trial action.\nKadanoff and Devreese-related optical absorption work clarify the low-temperature and frequency-response limits.\nHellwarth and Biaggio introduced practical multimode effective-frequency schemes for real polar lattices.\nFrost (2017) turned the finite-temperature Feynman/Hellwarth machinery into a first-principles mobility workflow for halide perovskites.\nMartin and Frost (2022) generalized the fictitious oscillator sector to multiple phonon modes and frequency-dependent multimode response.\nAdamowski, Gerlach, and Leschke developed broader functional-integral Gaussian-memory viewpoints that motivate the profile-function trial.","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"The Holstein and Peierls side follows the lattice-polaron path-integral tradition:","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"Holstein introduced molecular-crystal small-polaron transport.\nDe Raedt and Lagendijk developed path-integral lattice-polaron treatments.\nKornilovitch and collaborators showed how phonons can be integrated out to give continuous-time worldline Monte Carlo for lattice polarons.\nThe current package implements a lightweight CTMC variational analogue of that worldline picture, including full-periodic Holstein/Peierls bridge free energies and a general-d CTMC first-return mobility/response formalism with exact Holstein cloud sidebands and Peierls current-vertex sidebands.","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"Validated Fröhlich kernels are regression-tested against the historical literature values. Lattice mobility and response tests check mathematical consistency and limiting behavior; Peierls v1 is explicitly documented as a controlled closure awaiting stronger external benchmarks.","category":"page"},{"location":"#Where-To-Go-Next","page":"Home","title":"Where To Go Next","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"Use Examples for executable scripts covering the public workflows.\nUse Scientific Discussion for equations, path-integral structure, mobility kernels, and trial-family caveats.\nUse API Reference for exported symbols and docstrings.","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/#Scientific-Discussion","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/#Variational-Structure","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Variational Structure","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"The package implements the Feynman-Jensen variational idea in a model-agnostic form. After any exactly solvable degrees of freedom have been integrated out, the partition function is written as a path integral over a carrier path measure. A tractable trial process with action S0 gives","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"mathcal F\nle\nmathcal F_0\n+\nfrac1beta\nleftlangle\nS-S_0\nrightrangle_0 ","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"In code, the objective is decomposed as","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"free_energy(trial, parameters, beta) +\nentropy_cost(trial, parameters, beta) +\ninteraction_free_energy(model, trial, parameters, beta)","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"This is the central abstraction. The solver only manipulates parameters and bounds; the physics lives in methods attached to each model/trial pair.","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/#Fröhlich-Hamiltonian-And-Coupling","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Fröhlich Hamiltonian And Coupling","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"The continuum Fröhlich model describes a carrier coupled to longitudinal optical phonons through the macroscopic polar dielectric field. In the single-mode convention used by Feynman, the material enters through","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"alpha =\nfrac12\nfrac14piepsilon_0\nleft(\nfrac1epsilon_infty\n-\nfrac1epsilon_s\nright)\nfrace^2hbaromega\nsqrtfrac2m_bomegahbar ","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"For multimode materials, FrohlichMaterial stores mode-resolved couplings \\alpha_j and reduced phonon frequencies \\omega_j/\\omega_{\\mathrm{eff}}. The Hellwarth B effective frequency is used for Kelvin, THz, mobility, and length conversions, while the variational interaction itself still sums over the individual modes.","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/#Feynman-Gaussian-Process","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Feynman Gaussian Process","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"Feynman's 1955 insight was to integrate out the phonons exactly and replace the resulting retarded self-interacting electron path by a solvable Gaussian process: the electron is harmonically coupled to a fictitious coordinate. The public parameters are","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"wdelta\nqquad\nv = w + delta ","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"At zero temperature, the Feynman mean-square-displacement kernel is","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"D_F(tau)\n=\nfracw^2v^2tau\n+\nfracv^2-w^2v^3left(1-e^-vtauright)","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"The trial contribution is","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"A = -fracd2(v-w)\nqquad\nC = fracd4v(v^2-w^2)","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"and the interaction contribution is evaluated as","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"B =\nsum_j\nalpha_j K_d(omega_j)\nint_0^infty\nfrace^-omega_jtau\nsqrtomega_j D_F(tau)dtau ","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"The minimised zero-temperature energy is stored as","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"E_mathrmvar = -(A+B+C)","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"At finite temperature, D_F is replaced by the corresponding periodic The Brownian-bridge kernel and the phonon propagator become thermal. These are the Osaka/Hellwarth finite-temperature formulas used in the original PolaronMobility.jl workflow.","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/#Multiple-Gaussian-Modes","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Multiple Gaussian Modes","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"MultiGaussianTrial is the finite-mode extension used for Martin-Frost-style multimode variational work. The parameter order is","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"(w_1delta_1w_2delta_2ldots)\nqquad\nv_i = w_i+delta_i ","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"The zero-temperature displacement is","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"D(tau)\n=\ntau\n+\nsum_i\nfrach_iv_i^2\nleft\nfrac1-e^-v_itauv_i\n-\ntau\nright","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"with algebraic weights h_i obtained from the coupled fictitious oscillator spectrum. For one mode, this reduces exactly to Feynman's kernel, and the test suite enforces that reduction.","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"For more than one mode, the variational energy should be no higher than the one-mode value when the optimiser finds the same branch. Small improvements are expected; dramatic drops at weak or intermediate coupling should be treated as a warning sign.","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/#Profile-Functional-Gaussian-Trial","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Profile-Functional Gaussian Trial","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"ProfileGaussianTrial is the package's current implementation of the older general quadratic-memory functional idea associated with Adamowski, Gerlach, and Leschke. It represents a positive profile","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"Gamma(omega)\n=\nsum_i\na_i\nfracnu_i^2omega^2+nu_i^2\nqquad\na_i ge 0 ","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"The profile defines the Gaussian displacement through","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"D_Gamma(tau)\n=\nfrac2pi\nint_0^infty\nfrac1-cos(omegatau)\nomega^21+Gamma(omega)domega ","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"and the zero-temperature entropy/log-determinant contribution through","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"E_mathrmdet\n=\nfracd2pi\nint_0^infty\nleft\nlog(1+Gamma(omega))\n-\nfracGamma(omega)1+Gamma(omega)\nrightdomega ","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"For numerical stability, the package does not evaluate the displacement integral by direct quadrature. Since Γ is a rational positive profile, it decomposes","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"frac11+Gamma(omega)\n=\n1 + sum_j fracc_jomega^2+p_j^2","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"so the displacement is evaluated analytically as","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"D_Gamma(tau)\n=\ntau\n+\nsum_j\nfracc_jp_j^2\nleft\ntau\n-\nfrac1-e^-p_jtaup_j\nright ","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"At finite temperature, the same decomposition is used with the periodic oscillator kernel","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"O_p(taubeta)\n=\nfrac\n1+e^-pbeta-e^-ptau-e^p(tau-beta)\n\np(1-e^-pbeta)","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"and the Brownian bridge \\tau(1-\\tau/\\beta).","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"Feynman's one-mode trial is embedded exactly by choosing","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"Gamma_F(omega)\n=\nfracv^2-w^2omega^2+w^2","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"In the package basis this means basis_frequencies = [w] and a1 = (v^2-w^2)/w^2. The test suite checks that this profile reproduces the Feynman displacement, entropy correction, interaction, and total objective.","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/#Experimental-Nonlocal-Gaussian-Kernel","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Experimental Nonlocal Gaussian Kernel","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"NonlocalGaussianTrial is deliberately more provisional than ProfileGaussianTrial. It uses a finite nonlocal amplitude basis for the displacement kernel and a configurable quadratic regularizer as its entropy cost. Because that regularizer is not the Gaussian profile log determinant, the returned objective is a useful kernel-exploration score but not a validated variational upper bound.","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"If a nonlocal calculation returns an apparently much lower \"energy\" than the Feynman or profile result, do not interpret that as a physical variational improvement. It means the trial is outside the currently validated bounds of machinery. Use ProfileGaussianTrial for energy comparisons.","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/#Fröhlich-Mobility-And-Frequency-Response","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Fröhlich Mobility And Frequency Response","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"The one-mode Feynman solution feeds the historical mobility formulas:","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"FHIP low-temperature mobility from Feynman, Hellwarth, Iddings, and Platzman.\nKadanoff/Devreese low-temperature variants.\nHellwarth finite-temperature mobility and multimode effective-frequency handling.","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"The package also evaluates a frequency-dependent memory function \\Sigma(\\Omega). It stores","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"Z(Omega) = -iOmega+Sigma(Omega)\nqquad\nsigma(Omega) = Z(Omega)^-1","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"The scalar FHIP, Kadanoff, and Hellwarth mobility formulas assume the two-parameter Feynman action. For profile and nonlocal Gaussian trials, those literature-reference fields are reported as NaN, while the direct memory-function response is still evaluated from the trial displacement kernel.","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/#Lattice-Models-As-Poisson-CTMC-Variational-Problems","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Lattice Models As Poisson CTMC Variational Problems","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"The lattice models use a different solvable path measure from the continuum Fröhlich Gaussian trials. The electron lives on a hypercubic lattice, and the trial path is a symmetric continuous-time nearest-neighbour Markov chain with hopping rate \\kappa. The same PoissonTrial supports Holstein site coupling, Peierls bond coupling, and compatible composites.","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"The free CTMC contribution and relative-entropy rate for changing the bare hopping J to the variational rate \\kappa are","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"F_0(kappa)=-2dkappa\nqquad\nS_rm rel(kappa)=2dkappalogfrackappaJ","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"The hypercubic CTMC propagator factorises:","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"P_mathbf r^(d)(t)=\ne^-2dkappa tprod_mu=1^d I_r_mu(2kappa t)","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"The package names the return and nearest-neighbour components","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"q_0(t)=lefte^-2kappa tI_0(2kappa t)right^d","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"q_1(t)=e^-2dkappa tI_1(2kappa t)I_0(2kappa t)^d-1","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"In code, lattice_q0 and lattice_q1 evaluate these with exponentially scaled Bessel functions, so the formulas are stable for d = 1, 2, 3 and large arguments.","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/#Holstein-CTMC-Free-Energy","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Holstein CTMC Free Energy","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"The reduced Holstein Hamiltonian is","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"H_H=\n-Jsum_langle ijrangle(c_i^dagger c_j+c_j^dagger c_i)\n+omega_Hsum_i b_i^dagger b_i\n+gsum_i n_i(b_i+b_i^dagger)","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"After integrating out the local Einstein phonons, the lattice path acquires a retarded attraction at times when it occupies the same site. At a finite inverse temperature, the package uses","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"D_beta(uomega)=\nfrace^-omega u+e^-omega(beta-u)1-e^-betaomega","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"and the periodic CTMC bridge","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"C_rm site(ubeta)=\nfracq_0(u)q_0(beta-u)q_0(beta)","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"The variational objective is","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"F_rm var^H(kappabeta)=\n-2dkappa+2dkappalogfrackappaJ\n-\nfracg^22\nint_0^beta D_beta(uomega_H)C_rm site(ubeta)du","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"At zero temperature, this becomes","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"F_rm var^H(kappainfty)=\n-2dkappa+2dkappalogfrackappaJ\n-\ng^2int_0^infty e^-omega_Httextive_0(2kappa t)^ddt","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"For d = 1, the integral reduces to","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"int_0^infty e^-omega_Hte^-2kappa tI_0(2kappa t)dt\n=\nfrac1sqrtomega_H(omega_H+4kappa)","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/#Peierls-Bond-Coupled-Lattice-Model","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Peierls Bond-Coupled Lattice Model","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"The standalone Peierls model moves the electron-phonon coupling from site density to bond hopping modulation:","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"H_P=\n-Jsum_langle ijrangleB_ij\n+omega_Psum_b a_b^dagger a_b\n+g_Psum_b B_b(a_b+a_b^dagger)\nqquad\nB_ij=c_i^dagger c_j+c_j^dagger c_i","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"PeierlsMaterial follows the same boundary convention as HolsteinMaterial: a relaxation energy and phonon energy define the reduced coupling,","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"g_P=sqrtfracE_Phnu_P","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"The Peierls influence depends on bond-order correlations. The periodic bond bridge used in the package is","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"C_rm bond^+(ubeta)=\n2dfracq_0(u)q_0(beta-u)+q_1(u)q_1(beta-u)q_0(beta)","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"The finite-temperature Peierls interaction term is","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"F_P(kappabeta)=\n-fracg_P^22\nint_0^beta D_beta(uomega_P)C_rm bond^+(ubeta)du","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"At zero temperature,","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"F_P(kappainfty)=\n-fracg_P^22\nint_0^infty e^-omega_Pt\n2dtextive_0(2kappa t)+textive_1(2kappa t)\ntextive_0(2kappa t)^d-1dt","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"The factor 1/2 is part of the Gaussian influence prefactor. The helper peierls_integral_d returns the full 2d[...] bond integral; interaction_free_energy(::PeierlsModel, ...) multiplies it by -g_P^2/2.","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/#Lattice-Mobility-And-Frequency-Response","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Lattice Mobility And Frequency Response","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"The lattice response implemented in the package is a CTMC first-return current-blip projection. It is analogous in spirit to building a response on top of an optimised solvable trial process, but it is not the continuum FHIP memory-function construction. Any older lattice \"memory-function\" wording in the project should therefore be read historically rather than as the active runtime theory.","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"Conceptually, the lattice calculation has two pieces:","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"the variational free energy chooses the effective hopping rate \\kappa from periodic CTMC bridge correlations; and\nthe transport calculation inserts a current blip into that optimised CTMC path measure and dresses it with the exact phonon factor appropriate to the model.","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"The electron dynamics are encoded in the first-return kernel, while the phonons enter through sideband weights multiplying that kernel.","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"Current insertions select hop-like path segments. The duration distribution is approximated by the CTMC first-return kernel from a nearest-neighbour site back to the origin:","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"widehat f_ato0^(d)(s)=fracG_a^(d)(s)G_0^(d)(s)","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"Using the lattice resolvent identity, the package evaluates this as","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"widehat f_ato0^(d)(s)=\nfracs+2dkappa-G_0^(d)(s)^-12dkappa","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"where","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"G_0^(d)(s)=int_0^infty e^-sttextive_0(2kappa t)^ddt\nqquad Re s0","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"For d = 1, this gives the analytic expression","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"widehat f_1to0^(1)(s)=\nfracs+2kappa-sqrts(s+4kappa)2kappa","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"For d = 2, the return Green's function is evaluated through the square-lattice elliptic-integral form","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"G_0^(2)(s)=\nfrac2pi(s+4kappa)\nKleftleft(frac4kappas+4kapparight)^2right","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"For d = 3, the package uses the cubic-lattice reduction","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"G_0^(3)(s)=\nfrac1piint_0^pi\nG_0^(2)left(s+2kappa(1-cos q)right)dq","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"So the standard d = 2, 3 Holstein and Peierls transport calculations do not repeatedly integrate the oscillatory 0..∞ Bessel/Laplace kernel. The small positive broadening \\epsilon fixes the retarded sheet through s = \\epsilon - i\\nu.","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"The Einstein scale is retained as a diagnostic,","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"mu_E=betakappa","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"Given transport sidebands (\\nu_m,w_m), the reduced kernel is","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"K(Omega)=\nsum_m w_mwidehat f_ato0^(d)(epsilon-i(Omega+nu_m))","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"The package reports","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"mu(Omega)=mu_EK(Omega)\nqquad\nsigma(Omega)=mu(Omega)\nqquad\nZ(Omega)=sigma(Omega)^-1","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"At zero frequency,","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"mu_rm DC=betakappatextReK(0)","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"At zero temperature, this Einstein prefactor diverges, so the package treats DC and optical response separately. The DC mobility remains infinite, but fora  finite frequency, the reported reduced optical response is","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"mu(Omega)=sigma(Omega)=K(Omega) qquad Omega neq 0 T=0","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"with Z(\\Omega)=K(\\Omega)^{-1}. This is the natural reduced current-current normalisation of the CTMC first-return/blip ansatz and keeps the Holstein and Peierls optical spectra are finite.","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"Thus, the lattice mobility is not obtained by first defining a separate force-memory function and then inverting a Drude-like impedance. Instead, the package evaluates the retarded CTMC first-return kernel directly at the phonon-shifted frequencies generated by the blip cloud or current vertex.","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/#Holstein,-Peierls,-And-Composite-Transport-Sidebands","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Holstein, Peierls, And Composite Transport Sidebands","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"Holstein transport uses the exact current-blip cloud factor","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"C_H(t)=\nexp-S_H C_beta(1-cosomega_H t)\nexpiS_Hsinomega_Ht\nqquad\nS_H=2(gomega_H)^2","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"where C_\\beta = coth(\\beta\\omega_H/2). At zero temperature, this is a Poisson ladder. At finite temperature, the package evaluates the equivalent Bessel sideband weights, so the runtime response is a direct exact-cloud sideband sum over the first-return kernel rather than a separate memory closure.","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"Peierls transport is different. Since the Peierls phonon modulates the current vertex itself, the normalised vertex cloud is","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"mathcal C_P(t)=\nfracJ_rm resp^2+g_P^2D_P^(t)J_rm resp^2+g_P^2D_P^(0)","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"Here, J_resp is selected by response_hopping, with default :bare. At finite temperature,","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"D_P^(t)=(N_P+1)e^-iomega_Pt+N_Pe^iomega_Pt","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"Thus, Peierls has one zero-phonon current channel and \\pm\\omega_P phonon-assisted channels. It is not an exponentiated Franck-Condon ladder unless the hopping depends nonlinearly on displacement. In the code, this means the Peierls response is assembled from a small exact sideband list attached directly to the CTMC first-return kernel; it is not a fallback renewal approximation and not a lattice memory-function ansatz.","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"For independent Holstein and Peierls baths, the composite transport cloud is the product","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"C_HP(t)=C_H(t)mathcal C_P(t)","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"so the sideband list is the convolution of Holstein and Peierls sidebands. This is the response-side analogue of adding independent influence functionals in the free energy. If \\omega_H \\neq \\omega_P, the implementation keeps the actual shifted frequencies rather than forcing the composite transport onto one integer phonon ladder. Shared-mode Holstein-Peierls cross terms are not included.","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/#Combining-Lattice-Influence-Functionals","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Combining Lattice Influence Functionals","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"Holstein and Peierls models live on the same lattice path space when they use the same dimension, hopping scale, and PoissonTrial. The composite model, therefore, adds independent influence functionals on the same path measure:","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"F_rm int^rm composite(kappabeta)=sum_mF_rm int^(m)(kappabeta)","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"The corresponding code is:","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"holstein = holstein_poisson_problem(hopping = 1.0, phonon_frequency = 1.0, coupling = 0.4)\npeierls = peierls_poisson_problem(hopping = 1.0, phonon_frequency = 0.8, coupling = 0.35)\n\nproblem = VariationalProblem(\n    combine_models(holstein.model, peierls.model),\n    PoissonTrial(dimension = 1, bare_hopping = 1.0),\n)\nresult = solve(problem; temperatures = [1.0], frequencies = [0.0, 0.5])","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"For material-derived rubrene calculations, rubrene_holstein_peierls_problem builds both Ordejón Table II material models and reduces them to a shared Holstein phonon reference frequency before composition.","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"For transport-focused studies, the package also exposes guide-style helpers that can reuse a frozen zero-temperature optimum:","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"rows = holstein_peierls_transport_sweep(\n    problem;\n    temperatures = 0.05:0.05:0.5,\n    frequencies = [0.0, 0.25, 0.5],\n    kappa_source = :zero_temperature,\n)","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"These rows expose mobility, mobility_einstein, mobility_factor, conductivity_real, conductivity_imag, sideband normalisation diagnostics, and whether the rate came from :zero_temperature or :per_temperature.","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/#Limiting-Regimes","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Limiting Regimes","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"Useful analytical limits are encoded in examples and tests because they are excellent guardrails for future model additions.","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"For Fröhlich polarons, weak coupling gives the perturbative energy E \\sim -\\alpha and the Feynman parameters remain close to the bare oscillator scale. In the package convention, this is often summarised as v,w -> 3ω for the weak-coupling initial branch. At strong coupling, the optimised fictitious oscillator softens toward the phonon scale, w -> \\omega, while","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"v sim frac4alpha^29pi","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"Hellwarth's finite-temperature mobility decreases with thermal phonon occupation. Adiabatic versus antiadiabatic behaviour is read through the relative carrier and phonon time scales: slow phonons produce long memory, while fast phonons produce short retarded kernels.","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"For Holstein polarons, zero coupling removes the interaction and the Donsker-Varadhan objective is minimised at the bare rate,","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"kappa to J ","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"Weak coupling is obtained by evaluating the retarded interaction at the bare rate. In the strong antiadiabatic/localised limit, the leading energy is the Lang-Firsov shift","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"-E_p = -fracg^2omega_0","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"with exponentially narrowed hopping, schematically","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"-E_p - 2dJexp-(gomega_0)^2","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"High temperature shrinks the imaginary-time memory through \\coth(\\beta\\omega_0/2) and the finite \\beta integration window. The adiabatic limit has J/\\omega_0 >> 1; the antiadiabatic limit has J/\\omega_0 << 1.","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"For Peierls polarons, zero Peierls coupling recovers the bare Poisson walk or, in a composite model, the remaining component. Weak Peierls corrections scale as -g_P^2. Antiadiabatic Peierls phonons make the bond memory short-ranged; adiabatic Peierls phonons create long-lived bond modulation, the variational analogue of dynamic disorder.","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/#Tables,-Sweeps,-And-Plots","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Tables, Sweeps, And Plots","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"solve returns typed result structs. Table helpers flatten those into NamedTuple rows:","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"solution_table(result)\nmobility_table(result)\nresponse_table(result)","category":"page"},{"location":"scientific_discussion/","page":"Scientific Discussion","title":"Scientific Discussion","text":"Continuation sweeps warm-start forward and backward branches and selects the lower-free-energy row. Frequency sweeps optimise once per model/coupling and temperature point, then evaluate the response on the requested frequency grid without reoptimizing per frequency.","category":"page"}]
